Interactively Explore in Real-Time

Description

This exercise introduces you to App Designer instrument panel apps that let you tune parameters and visualize signals of your real-time application. You can easily build new instrument panels using MATLAB App Designer, which is the recommended environment for building apps in MATLAB.
Instrument panel apps come in hand whenever you would like to control and monitor your real-time application using a custom user interface or human-machine interface (HMI). This might for instance be of interest if you would like other users, to interact with the real-time applicaiton, for instance, to fine tune parameters or collect data for post processing of your current motor control design. MATLAB apps can be packed into a single file that can be easily shared with other users (see image below).

Run Electric Motor Control Instrument Panel App

myApp = userControlApp;
You can also run the instrument panel app from the project shortcut by clingin in the 'launchApp' shortcut.

Interact and Explore with Your Current Prototype Design in Real-Time

The Electric Motor Control instrument panel app included in this reference application allows you to:
  • Switch between RCP and HIL demo configurations and open respective models;
  • Easily connect to the target computer;
  • Build and download real-time application to the target computer;
  • Interactively control the electric motor speed and visualize data in real-time,
  • Open Simulation Data Inspector to inspect and compare data from different real-time simulation runs

Explore the App with App Designer

appdesigner('userControlApp.mlapp');
App Designer integrates the two primary tasks of app building – laying out the visual components of a graphical user interface (GUI) and programming app behavior. App Designer offers you a set of standard components such as buttons, check boxes, trees, and drop-down lists. It also provides controls such as gauges, lamps, knobs, and switches that let you replicate the look and actions of instrumentation panels. Container components, such as tabs, panels, and grid layouts to organize your user interface.
To design an user interface you simply drag and drop visual components to the design canvas and use alignment hints to get a precise layout. App Designer automatically generates the object-oriented code that specifies the app’s layout and design. Then, by using the integrated version of the MATLAB Editor, you can define your app’s behavior.

Close the App

close(app.UIFigure);
close(myApp);
